{
  "id": "school.cases",
  "order": 3,
  "title": {
    "en": "To, At, From",
    "uz": "Kelishiklar"
  },
  "blurb": "Three endings that replace all your prepositions",
  "estimatedMinutes": 3,
  "prerequisites": [
    "school.suffixes"
  ],
  "sections": [
    {
      "heading": "Cases do what prepositions do",
      "body": [
        "Where English puts little words **before** a noun — to the house, at the house, from the house — Uzbek clips an ending **onto** the noun. These endings are called **cases**, and three of them will carry you through your whole trip."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "uzbek": "uyga",
          "english": "to the house",
          "breakdown": [
            "uy",
            "ga"
          ],
          "gloss": [
            "house",
            "to"
          ]
        },
        {
          "uzbek": "uyda",
          "english": "at the house",
          "breakdown": [
            "uy",
            "da"
          ],
          "gloss": [
            "house",
            "at"
          ]
        },
        {
          "uzbek": "uydan",
          "english": "from the house",
          "breakdown": [
            "uy",
            "dan"
          ],
          "gloss": [
            "house",
            "from"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "heading": "The big three for travellers",
      "body": [
        "**-ga** goes: Toshkentga — to Tashkent. **-da** stays: mehmonxonada — at the hotel. **-dan** departs: Samarqanddan — from Samarkand.",
        "There are six cases in all — **-ni** marks a definite object, **-ning** means “of” — but -ga, -da and -dan are the daily workhorses."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "uzbek": "Toshkentga",
          "english": "to Tashkent",
          "breakdown": [
            "Toshkent",
            "ga"
          ],
          "gloss": [
            "Tashkent",
            "to"
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "exercises": [
    {
      "id": "choice-toga",
      "engine": "choice",
      "instruction": "Pick the right form of uy (house):",
      "prompt": "“to the house”",
      "options": [
        {
          "text": "uyga",
          "correct": true,
          "explain": "-ga points the way: to, towards."
        },
        {
          "text": "uyda",
          "explain": "-da means at or in — staying, not going."
        },
        {
          "text": "uydan",
          "explain": "-dan means from — the opposite direction!"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "choice-fromtash",
      "engine": "choice",
      "instruction": "Complete it: Men Toshkent___ kelaman — “I come FROM Tashkent”",
      "options": [
        {
          "text": "Toshkentdan",
          "correct": true,
          "explain": "-dan departs: from Tashkent."
        },
        {
          "text": "Toshkentga",
          "explain": "-ga would mean you're coming TO Tashkent."
        },
        {
          "text": "Toshkentda",
          "explain": "-da would leave you sitting IN Tashkent."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "choice-athotel",
      "engine": "choice",
      "instruction": "Pick the right ending:",
      "prompt": "“at the hotel”",
      "options": [
        {
          "text": "mehmonxonada",
          "correct": true,
          "explain": "-da stays: at, in, on."
        },
        {
          "text": "mehmonxonaga",
          "explain": "That's TO the hotel."
        },
        {
          "text": "mehmonxonadan",
          "explain": "That's FROM the hotel."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "build-totash",
      "engine": "build",
      "instruction": "Build the sentence: “I am going to Tashkent”",
      "tokens": [
        "Men",
        "Toshkentga",
        "boraman"
      ],
      "decoys": [
        "Toshkentdan",
        "uyda"
      ],
      "audioText": "Men Toshkentga boraman",
      "translation": "I am going to Tashkent."
    }
  ],
  "wrapUp": "-ga goes, -da stays, -dan departs. Clip the right ending onto the noun and you never need a preposition."
}
